            <section class="prose">
              <h2>How this island biogeography calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This tool implements the classic
                <strong>MacArthur–Wilson theory of island biogeography</strong>.
                It combines a <em>species–area relationship</em> with a simple
                <em>immigration–extinction balance</em>
                to estimate how many species an island can support at
                equilibrium.
              </p>

              <h3>1. Species–area relationship</h3>
              <p>
                Empirically, the number of species on an island increases with
                area following a power law:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>\[ S = c A^z \]</p>
                <ul>
                  <li>\(S\) = expected number of species</li>
                  <li>\(A\) = island area (km²)</li>
                  <li>\(c\) = constant (richness at 1 km²)</li>
                  <li>
                    \(z\) = slope of the species–area curve (typically
                    0.15–0.35)
                  </li>
                </ul>
              </div>
              <p>
                The calculator reports this value as the
                <strong>species–area prediction</strong> so you can compare it
                to the dynamic equilibrium from the immigration–extinction
                model.
              </p>

              <h3>2. Immigration and extinction curves</h3>
              <p>
                In MacArthur–Wilson theory, the number of species on an island
                changes through time as:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>\[ \frac{dS}{dt} = I(S) - E(S) \]</p>
                <p>At equilibrium, \(dS/dt = 0\), so \(I(S^*) = E(S^*)\).</p>
              </div>

              <h4>Immigration rate</h4>
              <p>
                Immigration is highest when the island is empty and declines as
                more species arrive. We approximate it with a linear function of
                the proportion of species already present:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  \[ I(S) = I_{\max}^{\text{eff}} \left(1 - \frac{S}{P}\right)
                  \]
                </p>
                <ul>
                  <li>\(P\) = mainland species pool</li>
                  <li>
                    \(I_{\max}^{\text{eff}}\) = effective maximum immigration
                    rate after accounting for distance
                  </li>
                </ul>
              </div>
              <p>
                Distance from the mainland reduces immigration. We model this
                with a simple exponential decay:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>\[ I_{\max}^{\text{eff}} = I_{\max} \, e^{-k D} \]</p>
                <ul>
                  <li>\(D\) = distance from mainland (km)</li>
                  <li>
                    \(k\) = distance effect parameter (controlled by the
                    “distance effect” slider)
                  </li>
                </ul>
              </div>

              <h4>Extinction rate</h4>
              <p>
                Extinction is lowest when few species are present and increases
                as the island fills up:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>\[ E(S) = E_{\max} \frac{S}{P} \]</p>
              </div>
              <p>
                In more detailed models, extinction also depends on area
                (smaller islands have higher extinction). You can mimic this by
                adjusting \(E_{\max}\) when you change area.
              </p>

              <h3>3. Equilibrium species richness and turnover</h3>
              <p>
                Setting immigration equal to extinction and solving for \(S\)
                gives the equilibrium number of species:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  \[ I_{\max}^{\text{eff}} \left(1 - \frac{S^*}{P}\right) =
                  E_{\max} \frac{S^*}{P} \]
                </p>
                <p>
                  \[ S^* = \frac{I_{\max}^{\text{eff}}}{I_{\max}^{\text{eff}} +
                  E_{\max}} \, P \]
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                The <strong>turnover rate</strong> at equilibrium is simply the
                immigration (or extinction) rate at \(S^*\):
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>\[ T = I(S^*) = E(S^*) \]</p>
              </div>
              <p>
                High turnover means species are frequently arriving and going
                extinct, even if the total number of species stays roughly
                constant.
              </p>

              <h2>How to interpret the sliders</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Mainland species pool \(P\)</strong> – larger regional
                  pools allow more species to colonize.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Island area \(A\)</strong> – affects the species–area
                  prediction; in reality it also lowers extinction.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Distance \(D\)</strong> – greater distance reduces
                  effective immigration.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>\(c\) and \(z\)</strong> – shape the species–area
                  curve; use literature values for your system if available.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>\(I_{\max}\)</strong> – baseline colonization rate for
                  a near island.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>\(E_{\max}\)</strong> – baseline extinction rate when
                  the island is saturated.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Distance effect \(k\)</strong> – how quickly
                  immigration declines with distance.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Worked example</h2>
              <p>Suppose you have:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>\(P = 200\) mainland species</li>
                <li>\(A = 100\) km²</li>
                <li>\(D = 100\) km</li>
                <li>\(c = 10\), \(z = 0.25\)</li>
                <li>\(I_{\max} = 0.8\), \(E_{\max} = 0.6\), \(k = 0.7\)</li>
              </ul>
              <p>Then:</p>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  Species–area prediction: \[ S_{\text{area}} = 10 \times
                  100^{0.25} \approx 31.6 \]
                </li>
                <li>
                  Effective immigration: \[ I_{\max}^{\text{eff}} = 0.8 e^{-0.7
                  \times 100} \approx 0 \] (for this parameterization, 100 km is
                  effectively “far”, so immigration is tiny).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Equilibrium richness: \[ S^* =
                  \frac{I_{\max}^{\text{eff}}}{I_{\max}^{\text{eff}} + 0.6}
                  \times 200 \approx 0 \]
                </li>
              </ol>
              <p>
                This illustrates how a strong distance effect can prevent
                colonization even if the island is large. Try reducing the
                distance effect parameter or distance to see how \(S^*\)
                increases.
              </p>

              <h2>Limitations and extensions</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  The model assumes a <strong>single habitat type</strong> and
                  ignores within-island heterogeneity.
                </li>
                <li>
                  All species are treated as
                  <strong>ecologically equivalent</strong> (same immigration and
                  extinction responses).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Rescue effects, speciation on islands, and human impacts are
                  not explicitly modeled.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                For teaching, this simple framework is powerful: it captures the
                core intuition that
                <strong
                  >large, near islands have more species and higher
                  turnover</strong
                >
                than small, far islands.
              </p>

              <h2>FAQ</h2>
              <h3>What is island biogeography?</h3>
              <p>
                Island biogeography is the study of how species richness on
                islands is shaped by colonization, extinction, island size, and
                isolation. The MacArthur–Wilson theory predicts a dynamic
                equilibrium where immigration and extinction rates balance.
              </p>

              <h3>How should I choose \(c\) and \(z\)?</h3>
              <p>
                Use published species–area relationships for similar taxa and
                regions when possible. If you do not have data, try \(z\)
                between 0.2 and 0.3 and adjust \(c\) so that predicted richness
                matches observed values for a reference island.
              </p>

              <h3>
                Can I use this for habitat fragments, not literal islands?
              </h3>
              <p>
                Yes. The same logic applies to forest fragments, mountaintops,
                ponds, or urban parks surrounded by inhospitable matrix. Just
                treat the mainland pool and distance in ecological terms.
              </p>

              <h3>Is this suitable for research?</h3>
              <p>
                This calculator is designed for
                <strong
                  >education, exploration, and quick back-of-the-envelope
                  estimates</strong
                >. For research, you should fit models directly to your data and
                consider more detailed processes (e.g., species-specific
                dispersal, metacommunity dynamics, or phylogenetic structure).
              </p>
